# Structured Logging Standards - 2025

Implement structured JSON logging with correlation IDs, proper levels, and PII redaction for complete observability.

**Justification:** Structured logs enable rapid debugging, compliance auditing, and automated alerting while protecting sensitive data.

## 🎯 Single Responsibility
This rule is ONLY responsible for defining HOW to log. Not when to log (that's in monitoring rules) or what to monitor (that's in metrics rules).

## 📋 Implementation Checklist

### Initial Setup
```markdown
- [ ] Choose logging library (Winston, Pino, Bunyan)
- [ ] Configure JSON output format
- [ ] Set up log levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR, FATAL)
- [ ] Implement correlation ID generation
- [ ] Configure PII redaction
- [ ] Set up log rotation
- [ ] Configure async logging for performance
```

## 📐 Log Structure Standard

### Required Fields (Every Log Entry)
```typescript
interface StandardLogEntry {
  // Metadata
  timestamp: string;        // ISO 8601 format
  level: LogLevel;         // DEBUG | INFO | WARN | ERROR | FATAL
  service: string;         // Service name from package.json
  version: string;         // Service version
  environment: string;     // dev | staging | prod
  
  // Correlation
  correlationId: string;   // Request correlation ID
  traceId?: string;       // OpenTelemetry trace ID
  spanId?: string;        // OpenTelemetry span ID
  userId?: string;        // Authenticated user ID (hashed)
  sessionId?: string;     // Session identifier
  
  // Context
  message: string;        // Human-readable message
  context?: object;       // Structured context data
  
  // Location
  file?: string;          // Source file
  function?: string;      // Function name
  line?: number;          // Line number
}
```

### Log Level Guidelines
```typescript
enum LogLevel {
  DEBUG = 'debug',    // Detailed diagnostic info (dev only)
  INFO = 'info',      // General informational messages
  WARN = 'warn',      // Warning conditions
  ERROR = 'error',    // Error conditions
  FATAL = 'fatal'     // Fatal errors requiring immediate attention
}

// Usage examples
logger.debug('Cache hit', { key, ttl });                    // DEBUG
logger.info('User login successful', { userId });           // INFO
logger.warn('Rate limit approaching', { current, max });    // WARN
logger.error('Database connection failed', { error });      // ERROR
logger.fatal('Service cannot start', { missingConfig });    // FATAL
```

## 🔒 PII Redaction

### Automatic Redaction Patterns
```typescript
const PII_PATTERNS = {
  email: /\b[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Z|a-z]{2,}\b/g,
  phone: /\b\d{3}[-.]?\d{3}[-.]?\d{4}\b/g,
  ssn: /\b\d{3}-\d{2}-\d{4}\b/g,
  creditCard: /\b\d{4}[\s-]?\d{4}[\s-]?\d{4}[\s-]?\d{4}\b/g,
  ipAddress: /\b(?:\d{1,3}\.){3}\d{1,3}\b/g,
  apiKey: /\b[A-Za-z0-9]{32,}\b/g,
};

// Redaction function
function redactPII(obj: any): any {
  const sensitiveFields = ['password', 'token', 'secret', 'apiKey', 'authorization'];
  // Implementation to recursively redact sensitive data
  return redactedObj;
}
```

